{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488317"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:36:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:36:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"411"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/411"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.28,0.6,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43682"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/411"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28683"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"387"},{"type":"tags","id":"1263"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1318"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43799"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43682"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old man presents with a four-month history of chest swelling. He has a 30 pack-year history and has drunk half a bottle of wine a day since his mid-twenties. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Examination reveals bilateral breast gland tissue enlargement (Image) as well as a painless, fluctuant mass confined to the right scrotum. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What one of the following is the most likely explanation for the physical sign shown?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Physiological variant","Large cell carcinoma of the lung","Testicular teratoma","Alcoholic liver disease","Adrenal tumour"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe picture shows gynaecomastia, defined as the benign proliferation of male breast tissue. Gynaecomastia may be associated with increased oestrogen and/or a decreased testosterone.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGynaecomastia can be a \u003Cstrong\u003Ephysiological variant \u003C/strong\u003Ein three age groups: neonates, adolescents and elderly males. This patient is middle-aged, which should raise suspicion for a non-physiological cause. In any case, more sinister differentials should be investigated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe significant alcohol history suggests this patient almost certainly has an element of \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcoholic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E. In chronic liver disease, the liver has a reduced ability to produce globulins including sex-hormone-binding globulin. In turn, the serum levels of sex hormones is increased.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stem describes a fluctuant testicular swelling, which may suggest a hydrocele, epididymal cyst or spermatocele. If the swelling is a hydrocele, this is probably idiopathic, without any sinister underlying cause. A testicular tumour would be firm, irregular and more likely to present in a young male. This man is aged 47 and most unlikely to have a testicular tumour. Additionally,\u003Cstrong\u003E testicular teratomas\u003C/strong\u003E are not typically associated with elevated sex hormones and would therefore be unlikely to cause gynaecomastia. Testicular tumours secreting human chorionic gonadotrophin (hCG) include Sertoli and Leydig cell tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal tumours \u003C/strong\u003Eproducing androgen precursors are a very rare cause of gynaecomastia. An abdominal CT may be considered in evaluation of this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGynaecomastia can be caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Elarge cell carcinoma of the lung\u003C/strong\u003E producing bHCG. This malignancy is strongly associated with smoking, so the patient is at risk. However, this paraneoplastic syndrome is rare.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gynaecomastia is an often-observed sign in alcoholic liver disease."],"references":["Dantanarayana N, Connolly J. An interesting case of gynaecomastia. Aust Fam Physician. 2016;45(1):53-55. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/january-february/an-interesting-case-of-gynaecomastia","Johnson R, Murad M. Gynecomastia: Pathophysiology, Evaluation, and Management. Mayo Clinic Proceedings. 2009;84(11):1010-1015. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2770912/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28683"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"411"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15888"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15888"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c5ffcfce-7c46-4641-8ee2-a79cee139fec.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c5ffcfce-7c46-4641-8ee2-a79cee139fec.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28683"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-25T14:32:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-25T14:32:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"411"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43682"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"}